Hey, new writefag here working on a story. I like what I have so far but I don't have a lot of experience writing fiction and I wanted to know what advice you had in order to speed up my pace a little. Does it just get faster with more experience?
Anonymous
  • Post

Anonymous Thu 09 Apr 2020 05:46:22 No.29499184 Report
Quoted By:
>>29499023
Depends.
If you haven't outlined, try a day of that.
Don't be afraid to take a day exploring your characters. The easier their reactions come to mind, the quicker you can write dialogue or action.
Take notes. I've had bits and revelations come in the shower and at work.
Get the whole thing down, then edit. Some people here prefer the write and release as quick as possible. Your first draft is never as good as the second or tenth.
One hundred words a day is better than zero.
Anonymous
  • Post
  • Report

Anonymous Thu 09 Apr 2020 05:53:16 No.29499269 Report
Quoted By:
>>29499023
Yeah. Big things to making and finishing a story are experience. I'm the writer of Shady Rest, and I'll give you some pointers.

1. Worldbuild. You need to build a believable setting, but dont go overboard with it. It's not going to follow every rule, law and scenario we would think of.

2. Storyboard. Developed a list of characters, how they're interacting, how they act/feel, etc. You need to have an outline for how the story is going to go.

3. Relax. Don't get nervous about pleasing everyone, you won't always be able to do that. Focus on what you like to write and control the story for yourself. That being said, don't completely ignore audience feedback, just know how to filter it.

One of the better techniques I use to prevent massive unwieldy exposition like that is do the dialogue first.
Then I'll add in tags for action or narration. Bare minimum on that since the scene is incomplete.
The last step is add in all the non-dialogue exposition or narration. At this point I know what people have said, why and the emotional context.
After that, it's all in the editing. I tend to add more detail there to tie scenes tighter. Other writers delete.

Only you can decide how you want to approach the story. My characters evolve out of the first draft, so the the worldbuilding comes from them.
My advice is give yourself a few days off. Reread your own brainstorming. See what still looks like a potential conflict between three characters. Write down the first three ideas about that conflict, quick and no more than 100 words.
Also, remember that the world of your characters makes sense to them. They don't know us. What expository detail you leave in should be absolutely necessary, and would require more words if shown through dialogue or action.

So even though I may disagree with your stances on many elements, it's your backstory. Take the time populating that world, and then it's interesting enough for me to set aside my views to see the why and where of your arguments lead to.
